-- Japan, South Korea, Malaysia, Taiwan, India: Asian Bonds, Currency Preview
-- B y   F r a n c e s   Y o o n
-- 2010-10-27T23:22:22Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-27/japan-south-korea-malaysia-taiwan-india-asian-bonds-currency-preview.html
The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  Japan: Chief Cabinet Secretary  Yoshito Sengoku  will hold
media briefings at 11 a.m. and 4 p.m. in Tokyo. The Bank of
Japan will have a one-day policy board meeting in Tokyo. BOJ
Governor  Masaaki Shirakawa  will hold a press briefing at 3:30
p.m. local time.  The Ministry of Finance will release at 8:50 a.m. its
report on Japanese and foreign investment flows for domestic and
overseas securities during the week ended Oct. 22.  The BOJ will publish its October report on the outlook for
the economy at 3 p.m. The Trade Ministry will release at 8:50
a.m. its report on retail sales. Sales rose 3.2 percent in
September from a year earlier, after a 4.3 percent increase in
August, according to a Bloomberg News survey.  The yield on the 0.8 percent government bond due September
2020 was at 0.945 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co.,
the nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.  The yen traded at 81.70 per dollar at 8:8 a.m. in Tokyo.  South Korea: The current-account surplus widened to $4.056
billion in September from $2.186 billion in August, the Bank of
Korea said in a statement in Seoul today.  The yield on the 3.75 note due June 2013 was 3.31 percent,
according to Korea Stock Exchange. The won traded at 1,128.24
per dollar.  India: Wholesale food price inflation data for the week
ended Oct. 16 will be released by the commerce ministry. Prices
increased 15.5 percent in the week ended Oct. 9 from a year
earlier.  The yield on the 7.8 percent bond due May 2020 was 8.15
percent. The rupee was at 44.58 per dollar.  Malaysia: The central bank will issue a total 180 million
ringgit ($57.8 million) of 91- and 182-day bills and 3 billion
ringgit of three-year bonds.  The yield on the 3.835 percent bond due August 2015 was
3.39 percent. The ringgit was at 3.1125 per dollar.  Taiwan: The central bank will auction NT$40 billion ($1.3
billion) of 20-year bonds and NT$30 billion of 273-day bills.  The yield on the 1.125 percent note due September 2020 was
1.272 percent. The Taiwan dollar was at NT$30.802 against the
greenback.  To contact the reporter on this story:
 Frances Yoon  in Seoul at 
 fyoon2@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
James Regan at 
 jregan16@bloomberg.net . 